CB Industrial, CIMB, Malaysia Building: Malaysia Equity Preview

-- B y   C h a n   T i e n   H i n
-- 
2011-08-03T00:14:29Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-03/cb-industrial-cimb-malaysia-building-malaysia-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies may
have unusual moves in  Malaysia  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the previous close, unless
stated otherwise.  The  FTSE Bursa Malaysia KLCI (FBMKLCI)  Index fell 0.2 percent to
1,554.85.        CB Industrial Product Holding Bhd. (CBP)  : The Malaysian
farm equipment maker’s engineering unit won a 171 million
ringgit ($57 million) contract to supply 100 fire and rescue
transport units to the Fire & Rescue Department of Malaysia,
according to a company statement. CB Industrial declined 1.2
percent to 4.16 ringgit.        CIMB Group Holdings Bhd. (CIMB)  : Malaysia’s second-
biggest banking group opened an office in Mumbai and signed a
business cooperation agreement with Kotak Mahindra Bank Ltd.,
marking its entry into the Indian market, according to a company
statement. CIMB slid 0.4 percent to 8.39 ringgit.       IOI Corp. (IOI MK): The palm-oil producer bought back 1.23
million of its shares for 6.36 million ringgit, a stock exchange
filing showed. IOI rose 0.2 percent to 5.15 ringgit.        K-One Technology Bhd. (KONE)  : The electronics components
maker said the Securities Commission has rejected its proposed
listing transfer to the stock exchange’s Main Market from the
Ace Market because it didn’t comply with the regulator’s equity
guidelines. The company will deliberate on its next course of
action and make an announcement if needed, K-One said in a
statement. The shares dropped 8.1 percent to 39.5 sen.        Malaysia Building Society (MBS)  Bhd: The mortgage
financing provider’s second-quarter net income surged 58 percent
from a year earlier to 78.2 million ringgit as revenue almost
doubled, according to a company statement. The shares fell 1.3
percent to 1.56 ringgit.        Malayan Banking Bhd. (MAY)  : The Employees Provident
Fund, Malaysia’s biggest pension fund, sold 4.1 million shares
in the nation’s largest banking group, a stock filing showed.
Shares of Malayan Banking, or Maybank, slid 0.2 percent to 8.82
ringgit.  To contact the reporter on this story:
